import BaseLayout from "../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";

const pageContent = "<div style=\"margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: 0px;\" class=\"pages\"><div id=\"C3546710557\" page-url=\"the-imperial-circuit-morocco-in-14-days\" class=\"page\"><a id=\"the-imperial-circuit-morocco-in-14-days\"></a><div class=\"page-layout\"><div class=\"page-content\"><bodycopy style=\"--fit-height: 10px; --resize-parent-width: 100%;\"><!--  ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════\n     THERE AND BACK AGAIN\n     Post: The Imperial Circuit: Morocco in 14 Days\n     Paste into a Cargo Code Block on the post page.\n     Assumes the global site CSS is already loaded.\n     ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════  -->\n\n\n<!--  ══ HERO ══  -->\n\n<div class=\"post-hero\">\n  <div class=\"post-route-strip\">\n    <span>Morocco</span>&nbsp;· \n&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<span>Marrakech</span>&nbsp;· \n&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<span>Rabat</span>&nbsp;· \n&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<span>Fes</span>&nbsp;· \n&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<span>Tangier</span>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"page-label\">Travel Chronicle &nbsp;· &nbsp;September 2025</div>\n\n  <h1 class=\"post-hero-title\">\n&nbsp; &nbsp; The Imperial Circuit:<br><em>Morocco in 14 Days</em>\n  </h1>\n\n  <p class=\"post-hero-sub\">\n&nbsp; &nbsp; Marrakech to Rabat to Fes to Tangier — a standalone journey through Morocco's old capitals, with the road running from red walls and desert light to medina shadow, Atlantic wind, and the northern strait.\n &nbsp;</p>\n\n  <div class=\"post-stats\">\n    <div class=\"stat\"><span class=\"stat-num\">14</span><span class=\"stat-label\">Days</span></div>\n    <div class=\"stat\"><span class=\"stat-num\">4</span><span class=\"stat-label\">Cities</span></div>\n    <div class=\"stat\"><span class=\"stat-num\">4</span><span class=\"stat-label\">Day Trips</span></div>\n    <div class=\"stat\"><span class=\"stat-num\">1</span><span class=\"stat-label\">Northbound Road</span></div>\n  </div>\n</div>\n\n\n<!--  ══ BODY ══  -->\n\n<div class=\"post-body\">\n\n  <!--  Opening Chronicle  -->\n  <div class=\"opening-prose\">\n    <div class=\"prose\">\n      <p class=\"drop-cap\">There are journeys that unfold by monument, and others by mood. Morocco, at least in this form, unfolds by intensification.</p>\n\n      <p>The traveller entered through Marrakech — through red walls and rooftop smoke and the great open lung of <em>Djemaa el-Fna</em> — and moved northward through older and more inward worlds: the composed quiet of Rabat, the tightening gravity of <a href=\"/2-days-in-fez-itinerary/\">Fes</a>, and at last Tangier, where Africa loosens itself toward Europe and every street seems to belong to more than one century at once. The road is not vast by continental standards, yet it feels large. The country changes its character so completely between cities that each arrival seems not a continuation, but a fresh argument about what Morocco is.</p>\n\n      <p>What makes the circuit work is not simply that these are important places. It is that they correct one another. Marrakech would be too much if it stood alone. Fes, by itself, might feel too enclosed. Tangier without the south behind it would lose some of its force. But taken in sequence, each city deepens the last. The traveller is first dazzled, then pressed inward, then released again to air, sea, and distance.</p>\n\n      <p>That is the road this journey takes: <em>red city first, then the capital pause, then the inward kingdom, and at last the lifting of the walls at the northern edge of the sea.</em></p>\n    </div>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"ornament\">✦ &nbsp; ✦ &nbsp; ✦</div>\n\n\n  <!--  ── CHAPTER I — MARRAKECH ──  -->\n\n  <div class=\"chapter-break\">\n    <div class=\"chapter-number\">Chapter I</div>\n    <h2 class=\"chapter-name\"><em>Marrakech</em></h2>\n    <p class=\"chapter-epithet\">The red beginning — spectacle, heat, old walls, and the first great shock of the road</p>\n    <div class=\"weather-badge\">\n      <span>☀</span>\n      <span class=\"w-hi\">High 33°</span>\n      <span>/</span>\n      <span class=\"w-lo\">Low 19°</span>\n      <span>— dry heat · nights merciful</span>\n    </div>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"narrative prose\">\n    <p>Marrakech is where Morocco chooses to announce itself without restraint. The traveller entered through Menara Airport in the evening, found the riad on Rue Bahia Bab Mellah, and began with dinner at <em>Restaurant Le Grand Bazar</em> — a gentle opening only in theory. Even a restrained first night in Marrakech feels like crossing into a brighter, dustier, more insistent version of the world. The city does not wait for the traveller to be ready. It simply begins.</p>\n\n    <p>And once it begins, it keeps unfolding. There was the long outward pull south toward <em>Ouarzazate</em> and <em>Aït Ben Haddou</em> — three hours through the High Atlas via the Tizi n'Tichka pass, where the mountains fold like old paper and the valleys below run in threads of green through ochre and grey. The kasbah at Aït Ben Haddou rose from its hillside the colour of the earth it was made from: still standing, still inhabited in its lower reaches, still indifferent to the centuries watching it. The return brought dinner at <em>Fluffy</em>, where the cooking is home-style and the welcome genuine — the right kind of quiet after a long and dramatic day.</p>\n\n    <p>Then the dense cultural reckoning: <em>Majorelle Garden</em> in the morning cool, the <em>Berber Museum</em>, the <em>Musée Yves Saint Laurent</em>, the <em>Photography Museum</em>, <em>Ben Youssef Medersa</em> — where the tilework and carved plaster of a fourteenth-century theological college press upon the visitor with the accumulated weight of ten thousand students who sat beneath that same geometry and read — and then the souk and <em>L'Envers Bar</em> for the evening. Later came the westward road to <em>Essaouira</em>, the wind city, where the Atlantic turns the light silver and the harbour smells of salt and cedar and grilled fish. Dinner on return at <em>Terrasses des Arts</em>.</p>\n\n    <p>The older-city day moved through <em>Kasbah Mosque</em>, the <em>Saadian Tombs</em>, <em>Dar Si Said</em>, the ruins of <em>El Badi Palace</em>, lunch at <em>Le Tanjia</em> — where the city's signature slow-cooked dish arrives in the clay vessel that gives it its name, fragrant with preserved lemon and cumin, as it has arrived for centuries — then the <em>Jewish Quarter</em>, <em>Bahia Palace</em>, the souk again, and dinner at <em>Blackchich</em>, where the rooftop looks out over the Mellah and the cocktails are strong and the night air carries the smell of woodsmoke and orange blossom from somewhere in the dark below. Then the road opened one final time to <em>Ouzoud Waterfall</em> — the falls dropping 110 metres through red rock gorge into spray that turns the air cool even in September — before dinner at <em>Azar</em>, and the departure morning gathered itself with <em>Koutoubia</em> and <em>Menara Gardens</em> and the station north.</p>\n\n    <p>This is a great deal of city, but Marrakech can bear a great deal. It is red wall, dust, tile, orange light, fruit stall, traffic, heat, and commerce in near-constant motion. Even when standing still the city seems to vibrate. <em>Djemaa el-Fna</em> sits at the centre of that spell like a public fever: by day a square of motion and opportunism, by night an illuminated republic of smoke, music, meat, performance, juice, persuasion, and risk. The traveller ate there on multiple evenings and it was different every time, which is the square's great talent.</p>\n\n    <p>Yet Marrakech would become exhausting if it offered only spectacle, and it is saved from that by its hidden rooms. <em>Majorelle</em> restores order and shade. <em>Ben Youssef</em> restores geometry and silence. <em>Bahia</em> reveals luxury hidden behind plain walls. <em>El Badi</em> gives ruin instead of ornament, absence instead of fullness. Even the souk, after enough time inside it, ceases to be merely market and becomes a test of the eye: how much colour, repetition, brass, cloth, spice, and human insistence can be absorbed before delight gives way to fatigue — and the answer, in Marrakech, is always more than you expect.</p>\n\n    <p>Marrakech also teaches the first important truth of the circuit: <em>Morocco is better when occasionally left.</em> After sea air in Essaouira, the medina feels denser. After mountain road and kasbah light, the red walls feel redder. After open country, the city's compression becomes part of its pleasure. Marrakech is not weakened by excursions. It is made legible by them.</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"practical\">\n    <div class=\"prac-header\">\n      <div class=\"prac-city\">📍 Marrakech</div>\n      <div class=\"prac-dates\">🗓 Days 1–7 &nbsp;· &nbsp;Rue Bahia Bab Mellah</div>\n    </div>\n\n    <div class=\"prac-section\">\n      <div class=\"prac-label\">Where to Eat</div>\n      <div class=\"prac-item\"><strong>Restaurant Le Grand Bazar</strong> — Solid medina kitchen, reliable for the first night. Order the lamb tagine. ~250–350 MAD/head.</div>\n      <div class=\"prac-item\"><strong>Fluffy</strong> — Home-style Moroccan cooking, beloved by those who know it. Modest prices, genuine welcome. ~150–200 MAD.</div>\n      <div class=\"prac-item\"><strong>Restaurant Grenade Marrakech</strong> — Franco-Moroccan, inventive. Good for a mid-stay dinner when you want something lighter than tagine.</div>\n      <div class=\"prac-item\"><strong>Le Tanjia</strong> — The city's signature slow-cooked dish in its clay vessel. One of the essential Marrakech meals. Book ahead. ~300–400 MAD/head.</div>\n      <div class=\"prac-item\"><strong>Terrasses des Arts</strong> — Long afternoons, coffee, medina views. Also strong for dinner on return from Essaouira.</div>\n      <div class=\"prac-item\"><strong>Blackchich</strong> — Rooftop bar and kitchen in the Mellah. Strong cocktails, good views, young crowd. Last-night material.</div>\n      <div class=\"prac-item\"><strong>Azar</strong> — Lebanese-Moroccan kitchen, reliable and lively. Good for the night before departure north.</div>\n    </div>\n\n    <div class=\"prac-section\">\n      <div class=\"prac-label\">Day Trips</div>\n      <div class=\"tip-row\"><strong>Ouarzazate &amp; Aït Ben Haddou</strong> — 3hrs south via Tizi n'Tichka. Hire a driver (~600–800 MAD return) or join a shared tour. Leave before 0800.</div>\n      <div class=\"tip-row\"><strong>Essaouira</strong> — 3hrs west. CTM bus ~100 MAD each way, or private taxi. Wind is constant — bring a layer even in September.</div>\n      <div class=\"tip-row\"><strong>Ouzoud Waterfalls</strong> — 2.5hrs northeast. Tour from Marrakech ~250 MAD, or hire a car. Arrive early. Cooler than the city — genuinely refreshing.</div>\n    </div>\n\n    <div class=\"prac-section\">\n      <div class=\"prac-label\">Tips &amp; Watch-Outs</div>\n      <div class=\"tip-row\">Download an offline map before entering the medina. Getting lost is fine. Getting lost hungry at midnight is not. Signal drops in the deep souks.</div>\n      <div class=\"tip-row\">Heat peaks early afternoon. Plan day trips to start before 0800, rest 1300–1600, and let the city reopen to you at 1700. The evening light on the ramparts is worth waiting for.</div>\n    </div>\n  </div>\n\n  <!--  MARRAKECH TOURS  -->\n  <div class=\"tours\" style=\"max-width:1100px; margin:0 auto 2rem;\">\n    <div class=\"tours-label\">Book for Marrakech</div>\n    <div class=\"tours-grid\">\n\n      <a class=\"tour-card\" href=\"https://www.viator.com/tours/Marrakech/Ait-ben-haddou-and-Ouarzazate-day-trip/d5408-100676P5?pid=P00295455&amp;mcid=42383&amp;medium=link\" rel=\"noopener\" target=\"_blank\">\n        <div class=\"tour-type\">Day Trip</div>\n        <div class=\"tour-name\">Aït Ben Haddou &amp; Ouarzazate via Tizi n'Tichka</div>\n        <div class=\"tour-meta\">The exact road taken — Atlas pass, UNESCO kasbah, film-set Ouarzazate. Round-trip from Marrakech.</div>\n        <div class=\"tour-footer\">\n          <span class=\"tour-price\">From ~$45 USD</span>\n          <span class=\"tour-link-label\">Book on Viator →</span>\n        </div>\n      </a>\n\n      <a class=\"tour-card\" href=\"https://www.viator.com/tours/Marrakech/Full-day-trip-to-Essaouira-Mogador-from-Marrakech/d5408-110964P2?pid=P00295455&amp;mcid=42383&amp;medium=link\" rel=\"noopener\" target=\"_blank\">\n        <div class=\"tour-type\">Day Trip</div>\n        <div class=\"tour-name\">Essaouira Full Day from Marrakech</div>\n        <div class=\"tour-meta\">Hotel pickup, guided tour of the wind city's medina and ramparts, return to Marrakech by evening.</div>\n        <div class=\"tour-footer\">\n          <span class=\"tour-price\">From ~$30 USD</span>\n          <span class=\"tour-link-label\">Book on Viator →</span>\n        </div>\n      </a>\n\n      <a class=\"tour-card\" href=\"https://www.viator.com/tours/Marrakech/Ouzoud-Waterfalls-Full-Day-Trip-from-Marrakech/d5408-7674P21?pid=P00295455&amp;mcid=42383&amp;medium=link\" rel=\"noopener\" target=\"_blank\">\n        <div class=\"tour-type\">Day Trip</div>\n        <div class=\"tour-name\">Ouzoud Waterfalls Full Day &amp; Boat Tour</div>\n        <div class=\"tour-meta\">North Africa's highest falls — 110m cascade, Barbary macaques, included boat ride. Round-trip from Marrakech.</div>\n        <div class=\"tour-footer\">\n          <span class=\"tour-price\">From ~$25 USD</span>\n          <span class=\"tour-link-label\">Book on Viator →</span>\n        </div>\n      </a>\n\n      <a class=\"tour-card\" href=\"https://www.viator.com/tours/Marrakech/Private-Tour-of-Marrakech/d5408-90460P1?pid=P00295455&amp;mcid=42383&amp;medium=link\" rel=\"noopener\" target=\"_blank\">\n        <div class=\"tour-type\">City Tour</div>\n        <div class=\"tour-name\">Private Half-Day Marrakech City Tour</div>\n        <div class=\"tour-meta\">Majorelle, Koutoubia, Bahia Palace, Jemaa el-Fna, and the souks — with a guide who knows what to skip.</div>\n        <div class=\"tour-footer\">\n          <span class=\"tour-price\">From ~$35 USD</span>\n          <span class=\"tour-link-label\">Book on Viator →</span>\n        </div>\n      </a>\n\n    </div>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"beat\">The south had done its work. The road could only tighten from here.</div>\n\n\n  <!--  ── CHAPTER II — RABAT ──  -->\n\n  <div class=\"chapter-break\">\n    <div class=\"chapter-number\">Chapter II</div>\n    <h2 class=\"chapter-name\"><em>Rabat</em></h2>\n    <p class=\"chapter-epithet\">The capital pause — quieter, necessary, and all the stronger for its restraint</p>\n    <div class=\"weather-badge\">\n      <span>🌤</span>\n      <span class=\"w-hi\">High 27°</span>\n      <span>/</span>\n      <span class=\"w-lo\">Low 17°</span>\n      <span>— sea breeze · cooler than the south</span>\n    </div>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"narrative prose\">\n    <p>The train north from Marrakech took three and a half hours, and Rabat arrived through the window with the mild, composed dignity of a capital that does not need to prove anything. It is the seat of government, the home of the king, and the most quietly underrated city on the circuit — which is precisely why it works so well as a hinge.</p>\n\n    <p>After the pressure and spectacle of Marrakech, Rabat belongs to a different register. It is not the city of sensory assault, nor the city of labyrinthine surrender. It is the city of <em>pause</em> — the breath between intensities, quieter in temperament, more composed in manner. The traveller walked the <em>Kasbah des Oudayas</em> in the late afternoon, the old Andalusian fortress at the mouth of the Bou Regreg river where the white lanes glow gold at dusk and the ramparts look out over the Atlantic with something close to contentment. Dinner at <em>Amber Bar</em>, where the Moroccan wine is served without apology and the food is serious. The traveller sat late over a good bottle and thought about the morning's train and the older city waiting ahead.</p>\n\n    <p>Some journeys need one city that does not insist upon itself too loudly. Without such a pause, the circuit becomes one long intensification with no room to breathe. Rabat is that room. <em>It is not the climax of the route, but the city that allows the next chapter to land more deeply.</em></p>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"practical\">\n    <div class=\"prac-header\">\n      <div class=\"prac-city\">📍 Rabat</div>\n      <div class=\"prac-dates\">🗓 Day 7 (overnight) &nbsp;· &nbsp;Ave Abou Faris Al Marini</div>\n    </div>\n\n    <div class=\"prac-section\">\n      <div class=\"prac-label\">Where to Eat &amp; Drink</div>\n      <div class=\"prac-item\"><strong>Amber Bar</strong> — One of the better wine lists in Morocco. Serious food, grown-up atmosphere in the Agdal quarter. ~300–400 MAD/head.</div>\n    </div>\n\n    <div class=\"prac-section\">\n      <div class=\"prac-label\">Getting There &amp; What to See</div>\n      <div class=\"prac-item\"><strong>Marrakech → Rabat</strong> — ONCF rail, ~3.5hrs, ~185 MAD 2nd class. Comfortable and reliable.</div>\n      <div class=\"prac-item\"><strong>Kasbah des Oudayas</strong> — Free to wander. Go late afternoon for light on the white walls. The Andalusian garden inside is a genuine refuge.</div>\n      <div class=\"prac-item\"><strong>Hassan Tower &amp; Mausoleum of Mohammed V</strong> — Morocco's most elegant royal monument. 20 minutes on foot from the medina, free entry.</div>\n    </div>\n\n    <div class=\"prac-section\">\n      <div class=\"prac-label\">Tips &amp; Watch-Outs</div>\n      <div class=\"tip-row\">One night is the right amount. A long afternoon and a good dinner — that is what Rabat asks for, and it is exactly what it gives back.</div>\n      <div class=\"tip-row\">The medina is far calmer than Marrakech or Fes. No guides will follow you. Wander freely.</div>\n    </div>\n  </div>\n\n  <!--  RABAT TOURS  -->\n  <div class=\"tours\" style=\"max-width:1100px; margin:0 auto 2rem;\">\n    <div class=\"tours-label\">Book for Rabat</div>\n    <div class=\"tours-grid\">\n\n      <a class=\"tour-card\" href=\"https://www.viator.com/tours/Rabat/Rabat-Private-City-Tour/d22447-52080P1?pid=P00295455&amp;mcid=42383&amp;medium=link\" rel=\"noopener\" target=\"_blank\">\n        <div class=\"tour-type\">City Tour</div>\n        <div class=\"tour-name\">Rabat Private City Tour</div>\n        <div class=\"tour-meta\">Kasbah des Oudayas, Hassan Tower, Mausoleum of Mohammed V — the capital's highlights with a private guide.</div>\n        <div class=\"tour-footer\">\n          <span class=\"tour-price\">From ~$40 USD</span>\n          <span class=\"tour-link-label\">Book on Viator →</span>\n        </div>\n      </a>\n\n    </div>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"beat\">Then the road turned inward.</div>\n\n\n  <!--  ── CHAPTER III — FES ──  -->\n\n  <div class=\"chapter-break\">\n    <div class=\"chapter-number\">Chapter III</div>\n    <h2 class=\"chapter-name\"><em>Fes</em></h2>\n    <p class=\"chapter-epithet\">The inward kingdom — gates, madrasas, tannery air, and the old gravity of scholarship</p>\n    <div class=\"weather-badge\">\n      <span>☀</span>\n      <span class=\"w-hi\">High 32°</span>\n      <span>/</span>\n      <span class=\"w-lo\">Low 17°</span>\n      <span>— inland heat · shade essential</span>\n    </div>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"narrative prose\">\n    <p>The train from Rabat to Fes took two and a half hours, and the city received the traveller in the manner it receives everyone: through a threshold. To enter <em>Bab Bou Jeloud</em> — the great blue gate — is to cross from the modern world into something that operates by an older logic. The lanes narrow immediately. The light changes. The air thickens with mint and tannin and woodsmoke. A mule appears from somewhere behind and the traveller presses against a wall tiled in geometric blue and the mule passes and the city closes back around like water over a stone.</p>\n\n    <p>The first afternoon was spent not by plunging immediately into the medina but by circling its edges — <em>Jardin Jnan Sbil</em>, <em>Bab Dekkakin</em>, the <em>Royal Palace</em>, the <em>Mellah</em> — before dinner above it all at <em>Palais de Mouda</em>, where the rooftop looks across the medina's lit hillside and the pastilla arrives in its sweet-savoury pastry crust dusted with sugar and cinnamon: one of those dishes that makes you understand why a city has endured twelve hundred years.</p>\n\n    <p>Then depth arrived. The true Fes day moved through <em>Al-Attarine Madrasa</em>, <em>Fontaine Nejjarine</em>, the <em>Museo Nejjarine</em>, lunch at <em>Restaurant Ryad Nejjarine</em> in the shade of its carved cedar square, then <em>Al-Qarawiyyin Mosque</em> — the oldest continuously operating university on earth — the tannery viewed from the leather shop balconies above, where the great vats of saffron and indigo and poppy red glow like something older than colour, <em>Place Seffarine</em> where the coppersmiths have been hammering for centuries and do not appear to be stopping, <em>Bou Inania Medersa</em>, <em>Bab Boujloud</em>, the <em>Zaouia of Moulay Idriss II</em>, the <em>Marinid Tombs</em> on the hill above the medina at last light — and then dinner at <em>Dar Roumana</em>, one of Fes's finest tables, where contemporary Fassi cooking meets a stillness that feels earned.</p>\n\n    <p>This is not a city arranged for easy admiration. Fes does not dazzle in the manner of Marrakech. It <em>encloses.</em> Its beauty is tighter, older, less interested in the traveller's comfort. Streets narrow as you go deeper. Texture thickens. Stone and cedar and tile feel less decorative than structural — as though they are not there to charm the outsider, but to continue an order of life that predates the outsider entirely.</p>\n\n    <p>The madrasas, fountains, workshops, and religious precincts do not merely decorate the old city. They explain its seriousness. Fes still feels, more than anywhere else on the route, like a place shaped by learning, devotion, and trade in equal measure. The tannery presents itself not as theatre but as labour that has become legend by persisting long enough. One does not drift through Fes. <em>One is drawn through it.</em></p>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"pull\">\n    <p>Where Marrakech dazzles, Fes endures. Where the south performs, the old north quietly insists.</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"practical\">\n    <div class=\"prac-header\">\n      <div class=\"prac-city\">📍 Fes</div>\n      <div class=\"prac-dates\">🗓 Days 8–10 &nbsp;· &nbsp;28 Znikat Hajjama, Medina</div>\n    </div>\n\n    <div class=\"prac-section\">\n      <div class=\"prac-label\">Where to Eat</div>\n      <div class=\"prac-item\"><strong>Palais de Mouda</strong> — Rooftop views over the medina. Order the pastilla. Grand setting, fair prices. ~300–400 MAD/head.</div>\n      <div class=\"prac-item\"><strong>Restaurant Ryad Nejjarine</strong> — Set lunch menu, excellent location overlooking the Nejjarine fountain square. ~200–250 MAD/head.</div>\n      <div class=\"prac-item\"><strong>Dar Roumana</strong> — The finest table in Fes. Contemporary Fassi cooking in a beautiful riad. Book well ahead. ~500–700 MAD/head. Worth every dirham.</div>\n    </div>\n\n    <div class=\"prac-section\">\n      <div class=\"prac-label\">Getting There</div>\n      <div class=\"prac-item\"><strong>Rabat → Fes</strong> — ONCF rail, ~2.5hrs, ~110 MAD 2nd class.</div>\n    </div>\n\n    <div class=\"prac-section\">\n      <div class=\"prac-label\">Tips &amp; Watch-Outs</div>\n      <div class=\"tip-row\">Have the riad send someone to meet you at Bab Bou Jeloud on arrival. Share your name and arrival time in advance. Do not attempt to find the riad alone the first time.</div>\n      <div class=\"tip-row\">Two nights is the minimum. Three is better. The city takes a full day just to begin to understand — and the second day is always richer than the first.</div>\n      <div class=\"tip-row\">The tannery smell is real. Mint sprigs are handed out at the entrance. Accept them.</div>\n    </div>\n  </div>\n\n  <!--  FES TOURS  -->\n  <div class=\"tours\" style=\"max-width:1100px; margin:0 auto 2rem;\">\n    <div class=\"tours-label\">Book for Fes</div>\n    <div class=\"tours-grid\">\n\n      <a class=\"tour-card\" href=\"https://www.viator.com/tours/Fez/Fez-Medina-4-Hour-Guided-Walking-Tour/d22151-32300P2?pid=P00295455&amp;mcid=42383&amp;medium=link\" rel=\"noopener\" target=\"_blank\">\n        <div class=\"tour-type\">Walking Tour</div>\n        <div class=\"tour-name\">Fes Medina 4-Hour Guided Walking Tour</div>\n        <div class=\"tour-meta\">Nejjarine Fountain, Al-Attarine Madrasa, Chouara Tannery, souks — the essential half-day with a local guide.</div>\n        <div class=\"tour-footer\">\n          <span class=\"tour-price\">From ~$25 USD</span>\n          <span class=\"tour-link-label\">Book on Viator →</span>\n        </div>\n      </a>\n\n      <a class=\"tour-card\" href=\"https://www.viator.com/tours/Fez/Fes-Guided-Tours-Full-Day/d22151-118008P2?pid=P00295455&amp;mcid=42383&amp;medium=link\" rel=\"noopener\" target=\"_blank\">\n        <div class=\"tour-type\">Full Day Tour</div>\n        <div class=\"tour-name\">Fes Private Full-Day Guided Tour</div>\n        <div class=\"tour-meta\">Bab Bou Jeloud to Dar Roumana via everything in between — the full medina itinerary with a certified private guide.</div>\n        <div class=\"tour-footer\">\n          <span class=\"tour-price\">From ~$55 USD</span>\n          <span class=\"tour-link-label\">Book on Viator →</span>\n        </div>\n      </a>\n\n    </div>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"beat\">And so the traveller turned their face to the final city, and the sea.</div>\n\n\n  <!--  ── CHAPTER IV — TANGIER ──  -->\n\n  <div class=\"chapter-break\">\n    <div class=\"chapter-number\">Chapter IV</div>\n    <h2 class=\"chapter-name\"><em>Tangier</em></h2>\n    <p class=\"chapter-epithet\">The lifting of the walls — sea wind, pastry counters, terraces, and the strait</p>\n    <div class=\"weather-badge\">\n      <span>🌊</span>\n      <span class=\"w-hi\">High 27°</span>\n      <span>/</span>\n      <span class=\"w-lo\">Low 18°</span>\n      <span>— Atlantic wind · cooler, looser, north-facing</span>\n    </div>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"narrative prose\">\n    <p>After Fes, Tangier feels like windows being opened. The train took four hours through the Rif foothills and arrived at <em>Tanger Ville</em> in the mid-afternoon, and the traveller moved almost immediately into the city's outward-facing character: <em>Musée Dar Niaba</em>, <em>Petit Socco</em>, <em>Terrasse des Paresseux</em> — the terrace of the idle, where the strait is visible on clear days and the light has a quality not found in any inland city — dinner at <em>El Contacto</em>, a medina restaurant with a fine fish kitchen and a wine list that leans Spanish, as befits a city that has always looked both ways across the water, and then the medina by night.</p>\n\n    <p>Then came the mountain interruption of <em>Chefchaouen</em> — three hours south into the Rif by grand taxi, a town so thoroughly painted in shades of cobalt and sky and faded indigo that it functions less as a place and more as a continuous act of aesthetic intention. The traveller arrived early, walked the medina before the midday crowds, climbed to the Spanish mosque for a view that encompasses the whole bowl of the valley, and returned to Tangier in time for dinner at <em>Restaurant le Saveur de Poisson</em>: no menu, no choices, the owner feeds you what he has decided, course after course of fish dishes that are exceptional and strange, in a room so covered in mirrors and trophies and certificates that the experience feels like being briefly adopted by a benevolent eccentric. It costs what it costs. It is worth considerably more.</p>\n\n    <p>The great Tangier day began at <em>Café Place de France</em> — the old grand café, the city in miniature, where the morning passes in coffee and newspaper and the particular pleasure of watching a city arrange itself around a square — then moved to the <em>Kasbah</em>, the <em>Tomb of Ibn Battouta</em>, <em>Patisserie Bab Medina</em>, <em>Librairie des Colonnes</em> (the famous bookshop that has sold Bowles and Burroughs and Mrabet since 1949 and smells accordingly), lunch at <em>Restaurant Walili</em>, then the <em>Kasbah Museum</em>, the <em>Phoenician Necropolis</em>, <em>Plage de Merkala</em>, <em>Café Hafa</em> on the cliff above the strait — where the tea comes with a view of Spain and the afternoon becomes theoretical — <em>St. Andrew's Church</em> (Anglican, 1894, with Arabic inscriptions inside the chancel arch, a detail that says more about Tangier than any guidebook), and dinner at <em>Al Achab</em>, where the rooftop looks out at the strait at last light and the lights of Tarifa begin to appear on the far side of the water.</p>\n\n    <p>Few itineraries reveal a city so fully. Tangier appears as what it has always been: port, threshold, compromise, dream, and residue. Arab and European at once. Sacred and cosmopolitan. Crumbling and self-aware. <em>Ibn Battouta</em> and <em>St. Andrew's</em> in the same afternoon. Pastries and necropolis. Kasbah and bookshop. Café and church and sea. It is a city of overlap, and that overlap is its true atmosphere.</p>\n\n    <p>That is what gives Tangier its peculiar aftertaste at the end of the circuit. It does not resolve the route; it loosens it. Marrakech had pushed the traveller into Morocco. Fes had pulled inward through old scholarly and devotional density. Tangier opens the body back out again — to sea wind, café terraces, neglected grandeur, and the permanent suggestion of departure. By the time the traveller reached the port on the final morning, the city had done exactly what a last city should do: <em>it had widened the story instead of closing it.</em></p>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"practical\">\n    <div class=\"prac-header\">\n      <div class=\"prac-city\">📍 Tangier</div>\n      <div class=\"prac-dates\">🗓 Days 11–14 &nbsp;· &nbsp;Rue Uruguay, Medina</div>\n    </div>\n\n    <div class=\"prac-section\">\n      <div class=\"prac-label\">Where to Eat</div>\n      <div class=\"prac-item\"><strong>El Contacto</strong> — Medina fish kitchen, Spanish-leaning wine list. Reliable and relaxed. ~250–350 MAD/head.</div>\n      <div class=\"prac-item\"><strong>Restaurant le Saveur de Poisson</strong> — No menu, fixed price (~250 MAD). Multiple courses of exceptional fish dishes. One of the strangest and best meals in Morocco. Book ahead — very few seats.</div>\n      <div class=\"prac-item\"><strong>Restaurant Walili</strong> — Traditional Moroccan set lunch. Honest, affordable, and good. ~150–200 MAD/head.</div>\n      <div class=\"prac-item\"><strong>Al Achab</strong> — Rooftop medina restaurant. Straightforward food, exceptional views of the strait at sunset. ~200–300 MAD/head.</div>\n    </div>\n\n    <div class=\"prac-section\">\n      <div class=\"prac-label\">Day Trip — Chefchaouen</div>\n      <div class=\"tip-row\">Grand taxi from Tangier, ~3hrs each way, ~80–100 MAD/person each way. Book the return for mid-afternoon. Arrive early — the medina before 0900 is a different place to the medina at noon.</div>\n    </div>\n\n    <div class=\"prac-section\">\n      <div class=\"prac-label\">Getting There</div>\n      <div class=\"prac-item\"><strong>Fes → Tangier</strong> — ONCF rail, ~4hrs, ~165 MAD 2nd class. Scenic through the Rif foothills.</div>\n    </div>\n\n    <div class=\"prac-section\">\n      <div class=\"prac-label\">Tips &amp; Watch-Outs</div>\n      <div class=\"tip-row\">Café Hafa on the cliff above the strait. Order mint tea. Bring something to read. Watch the ferries. No food — just tea and time and Spain in the distance. Non-negotiable.</div>\n      <div class=\"tip-row\">The American Legation Museum in the medina is free and genuinely interesting. Most visitors walk past it. Do not walk past it.</div>\n      <div class=\"tip-row\">Onward to Spain: FRS or Baleàries ferry, Tangier-Med port → Tarifa, ~35–40 minutes. Note that Tangier-Med is 45km east of the city — allow 1hr+ for the port transfer.</div>\n    </div>\n  </div>\n\n\n  <!--  TANGIER TOURS  -->\n  <div class=\"tours\" style=\"max-width:1100px; margin:0 auto 2rem;\">\n    <div class=\"tours-label\">Book for Tangier</div>\n    <div class=\"tours-grid\">\n\n      <a class=\"tour-card\" href=\"https://www.viator.com/tours/Tangier/Excursion-to-the-blue-city-from-Tangier/d4388-111117P2?pid=P00295455&amp;mcid=42383&amp;medium=link\" rel=\"noopener\" target=\"_blank\">\n        <div class=\"tour-type\">Day Trip</div>\n        <div class=\"tour-name\">Chefchaouen Day Trip from Tangier with Local Guide</div>\n        <div class=\"tour-meta\">The exact trip taken — hotel pickup, Rif Mountains drive, guided medina tour, return to Tangier. 1,000+ reviews.</div>\n        <div class=\"tour-footer\">\n          <span class=\"tour-price\">From ~$35 USD</span>\n          <span class=\"tour-link-label\">Book on Viator →</span>\n        </div>\n      </a>\n\n      <a class=\"tour-card\" href=\"https://www.viator.com/tours/Tangier/Chefchaouen-Private-Full-Day-Tour-from-Tangier/d4388-57410P10?pid=P00295455&amp;mcid=42383&amp;medium=link\" rel=\"noopener\" target=\"_blank\">\n        <div class=\"tour-type\">Day Trip · Private</div>\n        <div class=\"tour-name\">Private Chefchaouen Full Day from Tangier</div>\n        <div class=\"tour-meta\">Same route, private vehicle — better for those who want to set their own pace through the blue medina.</div>\n        <div class=\"tour-footer\">\n          <span class=\"tour-price\">From ~$65 USD</span>\n          <span class=\"tour-link-label\">Book on Viator →</span>\n        </div>\n      </a>\n\n      <a class=\"tour-card\" href=\"https://www.viator.com/tours/Tangier/Chefchaouen-Private-Tour-Starting-From-Tangier/d4388-10195P1?pid=P00295455&amp;mcid=42383&amp;medium=link\" rel=\"noopener\" target=\"_blank\">\n        <div class=\"tour-type\">City Tour</div>\n        <div class=\"tour-name\">Tangier City Tour — Kasbah, Medina &amp; Strait Views</div>\n        <div class=\"tour-meta\">Kasbah Museum, Petit Socco, Cap Spartel, Hercules Caves — the full Tangier day with a guide who knows the stories.</div>\n        <div class=\"tour-footer\">\n          <span class=\"tour-price\">From ~$40 USD</span>\n          <span class=\"tour-link-label\">Book on Viator →</span>\n        </div>\n      </a>\n\n    </div>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"practical\">\n    <div class=\"prac-label\">The Circuit at a Glance</div>\n\n    <!--  4-col route grid — fully inlined  -->\n    <div style=\"display:grid; grid-template-columns:repeat(4,minmax(0,1fr)); gap:1px; background:rgba(160,200,120,0.07); margin-top:1rem;\">\n\n      <div style=\"background:#0a0f08; padding:1.25rem 1.3rem; font-family:'Cormorant Garamond',serif; line-height:1.7;\">\n        <span style=\"display:block; font-size:10px; letter-spacing:0.32em; text-transform:uppercase; color:#5a8a3a; margin-bottom:0.35rem;\">Leg I</span>\n        <div style=\"font-family:'IM Fell English',Georgia,serif; font-size:1.25rem; color:#dde8d0; margin-bottom:0.45rem; line-height:1.2;\">Marrakech</div>\n        <div style=\"font-size:1rem; font-weight:300; color:rgba(221,232,208,0.58); line-height:1.65;\">Arrival into the red city, then outward to kasbah, coast, and waterfall, and back again into square, souk, palace, and night.</div>\n      </div>\n\n      <div style=\"background:#0a0f08; padding:1.25rem 1.3rem; font-family:'Cormorant Garamond',serif; line-height:1.7;\">\n        <span style=\"display:block; font-size:10px; letter-spacing:0.32em; text-transform:uppercase; color:#5a8a3a; margin-bottom:0.35rem;\">Leg II</span>\n        <div style=\"font-family:'IM Fell English',Georgia,serif; font-size:1.25rem; color:#dde8d0; margin-bottom:0.45rem; line-height:1.2;\">Rabat</div>\n        <div style=\"font-size:1rem; font-weight:300; color:rgba(221,232,208,0.58); line-height:1.65;\">A brief capital hinge in the middle of the road — quieter, cooler, and necessary before the medina closes in again.</div>\n      </div>\n\n      <div style=\"background:#0a0f08; padding:1.25rem 1.3rem; font-family:'Cormorant Garamond',serif; line-height:1.7;\">\n        <span style=\"display:block; font-size:10px; letter-spacing:0.32em; text-transform:uppercase; color:#5a8a3a; margin-bottom:0.35rem;\">Leg III</span>\n        <div style=\"font-family:'IM Fell English',Georgia,serif; font-size:1.25rem; color:#dde8d0; margin-bottom:0.45rem; line-height:1.2;\">Fes</div>\n        <div style=\"font-size:1rem; font-weight:300; color:rgba(221,232,208,0.58); line-height:1.65;\">Threshold first, depth after: gates, mellah, madrasa, fountain, tannery, old square, hill tomb, and nightfall over the medina.</div>\n      </div>\n\n      <div style=\"background:#0a0f08; padding:1.25rem 1.3rem; font-family:'Cormorant Garamond',serif; line-height:1.7;\">\n        <span style=\"display:block; font-size:10px; letter-spacing:0.32em; text-transform:uppercase; color:#5a8a3a; margin-bottom:0.35rem;\">Leg IV</span>\n        <div style=\"font-family:'IM Fell English',Georgia,serif; font-size:1.25rem; color:#dde8d0; margin-bottom:0.45rem; line-height:1.2;\">Tangier</div>\n        <div style=\"font-size:1rem; font-weight:300; color:rgba(221,232,208,0.58); line-height:1.65;\">Kasbah, terrace, pastry, bookshop, necropolis, sea wind, and the final opening of the route toward the strait and the north.</div>\n      </div>\n\n    </div>\n\n    <!--  2-col mini grid — fully inlined  -->\n    <div style=\"display:grid; grid-template-columns:repeat(2,minmax(0,1fr)); gap:1px; background:rgba(160,200,120,0.07); margin-top:0.8rem;\">\n\n      <div style=\"background:#0a0f08; padding:1rem 1.1rem; font-family:'Cormorant Garamond',serif; font-size:1rem; font-weight:300; color:rgba(221,232,208,0.62); line-height:1.6;\">\n        <span style=\"display:block; font-size:10px; letter-spacing:0.28em; text-transform:uppercase; color:#5a8a3a; margin-bottom:0.35rem; font-weight:400;\">Best Use of the Route</span>\n&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; Let each city contradict the last. Morocco reads better in sequence than in isolation.\n &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;</div>\n\n      <div style=\"background:#0a0f08; padding:1rem 1.1rem; font-family:'Cormorant Garamond',serif; font-size:1rem; font-weight:300; color:rgba(221,232,208,0.62); line-height:1.6;\">\n        <span style=\"display:block; font-size:10px; letter-spacing:0.28em; text-transform:uppercase; color:#5a8a3a; margin-bottom:0.35rem; font-weight:400;\">Dominant Moods</span>\n&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; Red walls, medina shadow, rooftop dusk, Atlantic wind, mountain blue, and the permanent suggestion of departure.\n &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;</div>\n\n    </div>\n  </div>\n\n  <!--  ── ROUTE AT A GLANCE ──\n       (section follows immediately above this closing div)  -->\n\n</div><!--  /post-body  -->\n\n\n<!--  ══ ITINERARY BLOCK ══  -->\n\n<div class=\"itin-block\">\n  <div class=\"itin-inner\">\n\n    <div class=\"itin-block-title\">How the Road Moves</div>\n\n    <div class=\"itin-meta\"><strong>Trip:</strong> Marrakech → Rabat → Fes → Tangier</div>\n    <div class=\"itin-meta\"><strong>Duration:</strong> 14 days</div>\n    <div class=\"itin-meta\"><strong>Best time to go:</strong> March–May or September–November. June–August is very hot inland. December–February is mild on the coast, cold in the mountains.</div>\n    <div class=\"itin-meta\"><strong>Travelled from:</strong> Australia — flights via Dubai, Doha or Casablanca</div>\n\n    <div class=\"itin-section-head\">Day by Day</div>\n    <div class=\"itin-days\">\n      <div class=\"itin-day-row\"><span class=\"itin-day-num\">Day 1</span>Arrive Marrakech. Check in to medina riad. Dinner at Restaurant Le Grand Bazar.</div>\n      <div class=\"itin-day-row\"><span class=\"itin-day-num\">Day 2</span>Day trip south to Ouarzazate &amp; Aït Ben Haddou via Tizi n'Tichka. Dinner at Fluffy.</div>\n      <div class=\"itin-day-row\"><span class=\"itin-day-num\">Day 3</span>Majorelle, Berber Museum, YSL Museum, Ben Youssef Medersa, medina souk. Drinks at L'Envers Bar.</div>\n      <div class=\"itin-day-row\"><span class=\"itin-day-num\">Day 4</span>Day trip west to Essaouira. Dinner at Terrasses des Arts on return.</div>\n      <div class=\"itin-day-row\"><span class=\"itin-day-num\">Day 5</span>Kasbah, Saadian Tombs, El Badi Palace, Bahia Palace. Lunch at Le Tanjia. Dinner at Blackchich rooftop.</div>\n      <div class=\"itin-day-row\"><span class=\"itin-day-num\">Day 6</span>Day trip to Ouzoud Waterfalls. Dinner at Azar.</div>\n      <div class=\"itin-day-row\"><span class=\"itin-day-num\">Day 7</span>Morning — Koutoubia &amp; Menara Gardens. Train Marrakech → Rabat (~3.5hrs). Kasbah des Oudayas. Dinner at Amber Bar.</div>\n      <div class=\"itin-day-row\"><span class=\"itin-day-num\">Day 8</span>Train Rabat → Fes (~2.5hrs). Arrive, circle the medina edges. First dinner at Palais de Mouda.</div>\n      <div class=\"itin-day-row\"><span class=\"itin-day-num\">Day 9</span>Full medina day — Al-Attarine, Nejjarine, Al-Qarawiyyin, tannery, Seffarine, Bou Inania, Marinid Tombs. Lunch at Ryad Nejjarine. Dinner at Dar Roumana.</div>\n      <div class=\"itin-day-row\"><span class=\"itin-day-num\">Day 10</span>Train Fes → Tangier (~4hrs). Arrive, settle, Petit Socco and terrace. Dinner at El Contacto.</div>\n      <div class=\"itin-day-row\"><span class=\"itin-day-num\">Day 11</span>Day trip to Chefchaouen (~3hrs each way). Dinner at Saveur de Poisson.</div>\n      <div class=\"itin-day-row\"><span class=\"itin-day-num\">Day 12</span>Café de France, Kasbah, Ibn Battouta, Librairie des Colonnes, Café Hafa. Lunch at Walili. Dinner at Al Achab.</div>\n      <div class=\"itin-day-row\"><span class=\"itin-day-num\">Day 13</span>Final morning in Tangier. Depart by ferry from Tangier-Med → Tarifa (~40 mins).</div>\n      <div class=\"itin-day-row\"><span class=\"itin-day-num\">Day 14</span>Onward from Tarifa — Andalusia awaits.</div>\n    </div>\n\n    <div class=\"itin-section-head\">Circuit Cards</div>\n\n    <div style=\"background:rgba(160,200,120,0.03); border:0.5px solid rgba(160,200,120,0.1); padding:2rem 2.3rem; margin:1.2rem 0;\">\n      <div style=\"font-size:10px; letter-spacing:0.35em; text-transform:uppercase; color:#5a8a3a; margin-bottom:0.8rem;\">Days 1–7 · Marrakech</div>\n      <div style=\"font-family:'Cormorant Garamond',serif; font-size:1.05rem; font-weight:300; color:rgba(221,232,208,0.62); line-height:1.8;\"><strong style=\"font-weight:400; color:rgba(221,232,208,0.86);\">Shape:</strong> Arrive softly, then let the city grow louder. Day trips outward to kasbah country, coast, and waterfall between full medina days. Marrakech teaches the traveller how much spectacle can still contain serious history.</div>\n    </div>\n\n    <div style=\"background:rgba(160,200,120,0.03); border:0.5px solid rgba(160,200,120,0.1); padding:2rem 2.3rem; margin:1.2rem 0;\">\n      <div style=\"font-size:10px; letter-spacing:0.35em; text-transform:uppercase; color:#5a8a3a; margin-bottom:0.8rem;\">Day 7 Overnight · Rabat</div>\n      <div style=\"font-family:'Cormorant Garamond',serif; font-size:1.05rem; font-weight:300; color:rgba(221,232,208,0.62); line-height:1.8;\"><strong style=\"font-weight:400; color:rgba(221,232,208,0.86);\">Shape:</strong> Do not overburden the capital. Let it breathe. It exists here as the pause between intensities — not the climax of the route, but the city that allows the next chapter to land more deeply.</div>\n    </div>\n\n    <div style=\"background:rgba(160,200,120,0.03); border:0.5px solid rgba(160,200,120,0.1); padding:2rem 2.3rem; margin:1.2rem 0;\">\n      <div style=\"font-size:10px; letter-spacing:0.35em; text-transform:uppercase; color:#5a8a3a; margin-bottom:0.8rem;\">Days 8–10 · Fes</div>\n      <div style=\"font-family:'Cormorant Garamond',serif; font-size:1.05rem; font-weight:300; color:rgba(221,232,208,0.62); line-height:1.8;\"><strong style=\"font-weight:400; color:rgba(221,232,208,0.86);\">Shape:</strong> Gates and perimeter first, then the true inward day of madrasa, fountain, mosque, tannery, square, shrine, and tomb. Fes narrows the road and makes the traveller move more carefully through it. Dinner at Dar Roumana is the reward for the full day's work.</div>\n    </div>\n\n    <div style=\"background:rgba(160,200,120,0.03); border:0.5px solid rgba(160,200,120,0.1); padding:2rem 2.3rem; margin:1.2rem 0;\">\n      <div style=\"font-size:10px; letter-spacing:0.35em; text-transform:uppercase; color:#5a8a3a; margin-bottom:0.8rem;\">Days 11–14 · Tangier</div>\n      <div style=\"font-family:'Cormorant Garamond',serif; font-size:1.05rem; font-weight:300; color:rgba(221,232,208,0.62); line-height:1.8;\"><strong style=\"font-weight:400; color:rgba(221,232,208,0.86);\">Shape:</strong> Arrive through terrace and medina, break the city open with Chefchaouen, then spend one full day letting Tangier reveal itself through café, kasbah, pastry, bookshop, necropolis, sea, and church. The final morning belongs to the port and the ferry north.</div>\n    </div>\n\n    <div class=\"itin-section-head\">Getting Around</div>\n    <div class=\"transport-note\"><strong>ONCF Rail:</strong> The backbone of the circuit. Marrakech–Rabat–Fes–Tangier is fully connected. 2nd class is comfortable and significantly cheaper than 1st. Book at oncf.ma for peak departures.</div>\n    <div class=\"transport-note\"><strong>Day trips:</strong> Grand taxis for routes not served by rail. Negotiate price before departure. CTM buses cover most routes as an alternative.</div>\n    <div class=\"transport-note\"><strong>Within medinas:</strong> Walking only. Car-free zones throughout. Petit taxis for the gap between medina and new city.</div>\n    <div class=\"transport-note\"><strong>To Spain:</strong> FRS or Baleàries ferry, Tangier-Med → Tarifa. ~35–40 minutes. Tangier-Med port is 45km east of the city — allow 1hr+ transfer time.</div>\n\n  </div>\n</div>\n\n\n<!--  ══ CLOSING CHRONICLE ══  -->\n\n<div class=\"post-closing\">\n  <div class=\"narrative prose\" style=\"max-width:820px; margin:0 auto;\">\n    <p>What remains from this route is not one image of Morocco, but several, each correcting the last: red walls at dusk in Marrakech; the square alive after dark; a madrasa courtyard in stillness; the density of Fes pressing inward through its thousand lanes; a rooftop dinner above the medina at the end of a long day of tannery and tile and old prayer; a blue mountain town three hours south into the Rif; and Tangier looking at once toward Africa and away from it, the strait barely eight miles wide and the lights of Spain already visible at the last dinner.</p>\n\n    <p>That is why the imperial circuit works. It is not merely a run of famous cities. It is a sequence of changing atmospheres, each one necessary to the next. The traveller does not leave with a single Morocco, neatly explained. They leave with a country of overlapping worlds: southern heat, imperial enclosure, Atlantic light, medina shadow, mountain blue, old devotion, and public theatre, all in fourteen days.</p>\n\n    <p>That is much nearer the truth of the place.</p>\n\n    <div class=\"pull\">\n      <p>The road begins in red dust and ends in sea wind, and between the two, Morocco keeps changing the shape of the traveller's gaze.</p>\n    </div>\n  </div>\n</div>\n\n\n<!--  ══ FURTHER READING ══  -->\n\n<div class=\"next-chronicles\">\n\n  <div class=\"next-label\">Further Reading</div>\n\n  <div class=\"posts-grid\">\n\n    <div class=\"post-card\">\n      <div class=\"post-region\"><a href=\"/coming-soon/\">Morocco</a></div>\n      <div class=\"post-title\">Into the Erg: Marrakech to the Sahara in Four Days</div>\n      <div class=\"post-excerpt\">The road south past Ouarzazate into the Draa Valley and the great dunes of Erg Chebbi — a deeper journey into the Morocco that lies beyond the imperial cities, where the colour of the land changes every hour.</div>\n      <div class=\"post-meta\">Coming Soon&nbsp;<span class=\"dot\"></span>&nbsp;Morocco</div>\n    </div>\n\n    <div class=\"post-card\">\n      <div class=\"post-region\"><a href=\"/10-days-in-sevilla/\">Spain · Andalusia</a></div>\n      <div class=\"post-title\">The Andalusian Arc: Seville, Córdoba and Cadiz in Ten Days</div>\n      <div class=\"post-excerpt\">Crossing the strait from Tangier into southern Spain — the natural continuation of the imperial circuit, where the Moorish world left its most beautiful mark on European stone and the food gets suddenly very good.</div>\n      <div class=\"post-meta\">Coming Soon&nbsp;<span class=\"dot\"></span>&nbsp;Spain</div>\n    </div>\n\n    <div class=\"post-card\">\n      <div class=\"post-region\"><a href=\"/coming-soon/\">Morocco</a></div>\n      <div class=\"post-title\">The Blue City Alone: Three Days in Chefchaouen</div>\n      <div class=\"post-excerpt\">For those who want more than a day trip — a full account of Morocco's most photographed medina, the Rif mountains above it, and the villages beyond the tourist centre where the blue paint runs thin.</div>\n      <div class=\"post-meta\">Coming Soon&nbsp;<span class=\"dot\"></span>&nbsp;Morocco</div>\n    </div>\n\n  </div>\n\n</div></bodycopy></div></div></div></div>";
